[1mNAME[0m[m
       visudo — edit the sudoers file[m
[m
[1mSYNOPSIS[0m[m
       [1mvisudo [22m[[1m-chIOPqsV[22m] [[[1m-f[22m] [4msudoers[24m][m
[m
[1mDESCRIPTION[0m[m
       [1mvisudo  [22medits  the  [4msudoers[24m file in a safe fashion, analogous to [4mvipw[24m(8).  [1mvisudo [22mlocks the [4msudoers[24m file against multiple simultaneous edits, performs[m
       basic validity checks, and checks for syntax errors before installing the edited file.  If the [4msudoers[24m file is currently being edited you will receive[m
       a message to try again later.[m
[m
       If the [4msudoers[24m file does not exist, it will be created unless the editor exits without writing to the file.[m
[m
       [1mvisudo [22mparses the [4msudoers[24m file after editing and will not save the changes if there is a syntax error.  Upon finding an error,  [1mvisudo  [22mwill  print  a[m
       message stating the line number(s) where the error occurred and the user will receive the “What now?” prompt.  At this point the user may enter ‘e’ to[m
       re-edit the [4msudoers[24m file, ‘x’ to exit without saving the changes, or ‘Q’ to quit and save changes.  The ‘Q’ option should be used with extreme caution[m
       because if [1mvisudo [22mbelieves there to be a syntax error, so will [1msudo[22m.  If ‘e’ is typed to edit the [4msudoers[24m file after a syntax error has been detected,[m
       the cursor will be placed on the line where the error occurred (if the editor supports this feature).[m
[m
       There are two [4msudoers[24m settings that determine which editor [1mvisudo [22mwill run.[m
[m
       editor      A  colon  (‘:’)  separated  list  of  editors  allowed  to  be  used  with  [1mvisudo[22m.  [1mvisudo [22mwill choose the editor that matches the user's[m
                   SUDO_EDITOR, VISUAL, or EDITOR environment variable if possible, or the first editor in the list that exists and is executable.  [1msudo [22mdoes[m
                   not preserve the SUDO_EDITOR, VISUAL, or EDITOR environment variables unless they are present in the [4menv_keep[24m list or the [4menv_reset[24m option[m
                   is disabled in the [4msudoers[24m file.  The default editor path is [4m/usr/bin/editor[24m which can be set at compile time via the  [1m--with-editor  [22mcon‐[m
                   figure option.[m
[m
       env_editor  If  set,  [1mvisudo  [22mwill use the value of the SUDO_EDITOR, VISUAL, or EDITOR environment variables before falling back on the default editor[m
                   list.  [1mvisudo [22mis typically run as root so this option may allow a user with [1mvisudo [22mprivileges to run arbitrary commands  as  root  without[m
                   logging.   An  alternative  is  to  place  a  colon-separated  list  of  “safe” editors in the [4meditor[24m variable.  [1mvisudo [22mwill then only use[m
                   SUDO_EDITOR, VISUAL, or EDITOR if they match a value specified in [4meditor[24m.  If the [4menv_reset[24m flag  is  enabled,  the  SUDO_EDITOR,  VISUAL,[m
                   and/or  EDITOR  environment  variables must be present in the [4menv_keep[24m list for the [4menv_editor[24m flag to function when [1mvisudo [22mis invoked via[m
                   [1msudo[22m.  The default value is [4mon[24m, which can be set at compile time via the [1m--with-env-editor [22mconfigure option.[m
[m
       The options are as follows:[m
[m
       [1m-c[22m, [1m--check[0m[m
               Enable [4mcheck-only[24m mode.  The existing [4msudoers[24m file (and any other files it includes) will be checked for syntax errors.  If the  path  to  the[m
